\section{Pipeline Integration}

\subsection{Motivation}

The cross-section formula
$d^2\sigma / dp_T d\eta = N_{\rm iso\,prompt}/(\varepsilon\cdot\mathcal{L}
\cdot \Delta)$ assumes that $\varepsilon$ --- constructed from MC ---
correctly captures the detector acceptance from which the data sample
is drawn. If MC and data disagree in their $(\eta,\phi)$ acceptance
because GEANT fails to emulate the full dead-tower list of the real
detector, $\varepsilon_{\rm code}$ is systematically larger than the
true $\varepsilon_{\rm data}$ and the measured cross-section is biased
low by a factor $\varepsilon_{\rm data}/\varepsilon_{\rm code}$.

A prior one-off diagnostic comparing photon10 MC to data in tower
indices (\texttt{plotting/plot\_tight\_etaphi\_compare.C}, Apr
2026) found a $\sim$14\% deficit at the tight level, but photon10 alone
has $\sim$250k tight clusters and a per-tower
$N_{\rm eff}\sim 3$, so the photon10-vs-data comparison could not
cleanly separate dead-tower effects from statistical noise. Moving the
fills into the official efficiency pipeline ($\mathcal{O}$(5$\times$)
more statistics via the lumi-weighted inclusive MC, identical cuts, no
vertex-cut drift) is the correct apples-to-apples diagnostic.

\subsection{Code changes}

Two files modified; MergeSim.C unchanged (plain TFileMerger handles
TH2F auto-hadd across per-sample runs).

\textbf{\texttt{efficiencytool/RecoEffCalculator\_TTreeReader.C}}:
\begin{itemize}
  \item Four new \texttt{TH2F*} pointers declared+allocated after the
  existing single-pointer MBD-QA TH2Ds (line range 892--912):
  \texttt{h\_etaphi\_tower\_\{preselect, common, tight, tight\_iso\}}.
  Axes are raw tower indices (96 $i\eta$ $\times$ 256 $i\phi$); no
  vertex-dependent $\eta,\phi$ smearing.
  \item \texttt{tower\_map\_et\_min} read from
  \texttt{analysis.tower\_map\_et\_min} in YAML with default 8.0 GeV
  (matches \texttt{plotcommon.h::ptRanges[0]}).
  \item Four \texttt{Fill()} call sites inside the cluster loop:
  (i) after ET gate + saturation cut, gated on
  ET$\ge$tower\_map\_et\_min (preselect, line 2047);
  (ii) inside the common-pass block (common, line 2364);
  (iii) after \texttt{tight = true} (tight, line 2453);
  (iv) same block, additionally gated on \texttt{iso} (tight+iso, line
  2457). All use the canonical per-event \texttt{weight} variable
  already consumed by the efficiency \texttt{FillWeighted} calls.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{\texttt{efficiencytool/CalculatePhotonYield.C}}: new block
before \texttt{fout->Write()} around line 1192 that opens
\texttt{\{eff\_outfile\}\_jet\_\{var\_type\}.root}, iterates the four
levels, Clones the signal TH2 from \texttt{fsimin}, Adds the jet TH2,
Writes as \texttt{h\_etaphi\_tower\_\{level\}\_mc\_inclusive}.
Additionally, in the non-MC-closure path, Clones and Writes the data
TH2 as \texttt{\_data}. So \texttt{Photon\_final\_\{var\_type\}.root}
ends up with 8 new histograms (4 levels $\times$ \{MC\_incl, data\}).

\subsection{Condor dispatch}

Two submit files added to support nominal-only production:
\texttt{oneforall\_tree\_double\_nom\_only.sub} queues the two
merge-feeder period configs through the DI TTree pipeline (Phase 1);
\texttt{oneforall\_nom\_only.sub} queues the bare all-range config
through \texttt{oneforall.sh} for Phase 2. Run executed
\texttt{2026-04-22}: Phase 1 cluster 1026116 (both period jobs finished
cleanly in $\sim$30 min each); Phase 2 cluster 1026118 (single job,
$\sim$25 min merge + data + 2$\times$ CalculatePhotonYield).

\subsection{Z-score: empirical R-distribution method}
\label{sec:rstat}

The lumi-weighted inclusive MC is a sum over multiple samples
(photon5/10/20, jet8/12/20/30/40) with per-event weights
$w_i = \sigma_i \cdot \mathcal{L}/\mathcal{L}_{\rm target} \cdot
w_{\rm vtx}$. Per-bin count is $\sum w_i$ with variance
$\sum w_i^2$, so the effective $N = (\sum w_i)^2 / \sum w_i^2$ can
differ from the Poisson expectation by orders of magnitude in
low-stats bins. The per-bin Poisson approximation used earlier in
this report is therefore invalid as a formal statistical estimator
for the weighted MC side.

\textbf{Replacement}: empirical z-score from the 1D distribution of
$R = p_{\rm data} / p_{\rm MC}$ across all filled bins.

\begin{enumerate}
  \item For each selection level, collect $R$ from every bin with
  $n_{\rm MC} > 0$ and $n_{\rm data} > 0$ (hard-dead bins excluded
  from the fit because they contribute $R=0$ outliers that would
  pull the center low).
  \item Compute a robust center: median of $R$, and
  $\sigma_{\rm MAD} = 1.4826 \cdot {\rm MAD}$ (median absolute
  deviation, the Gaussian-equivalent scale).
  \item Iteratively refine a core-Gaussian fit: start from
  $[{\rm median} - 1.5\sigma_{\rm MAD}, {\rm median} + 1.5\sigma_{\rm MAD}]$,
  compute mean and std inside the window, redefine window, iterate
  5 times. Converges to the width of the physics "bulk" peak,
  rejecting the heavy asymmetric tail driven by low-stats outliers.
  \item Define $z[i,j] = (R[i,j] - \mu_{\rm core}) /
  \sigma_{\rm core}$ with these empirical core parameters.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{figure}[H]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{\figdir/rdist_all_levels.pdf}
  \caption{$R = p_{\rm data}/p_{\rm MC}$ distribution at each
  selection level (preselect, common, tight, tight+iso). Dashed red =
  core-Gaussian fit after iterative 1.5-$\sigma$ clipping. Vertical
  dotted = core mean. The preselect and common distributions are
  reasonably Gaussian near the core ($\sigma_{\rm core} \sim 0.21
  \text{--} 0.27$). The tight distribution has a well-defined core
  near $R = 0.83$ (below 1, reflecting the shape-cut-driven
  dead-halo depression) but is broader
  ($\sigma_{\rm core} = 0.44$). Tight+iso has no meaningful core
  Gaussian --- the distribution is dominated by low-MC-stats outliers
  out to $R \gtrsim 10$, and the fit shown is unphysical; at this
  level only hard-dead bins are meaningfully flagged.}
  \label{fig:rdist}
\end{figure}

Under the empirical R-stat method:

\begin{itemize}
  \item $R \ge 0$ bounds the lower tail. At common-level
  $\mu_{\rm core} - 5\sigma_{\rm core} < 0$, so z$<$-5 picks up NO
  non-hard-dead bins --- the \texttt{*\_zlt5} mask therefore
  collapses to the \texttt{*\_harddead} mask at every level.
  \item At tight/tight+iso levels, the empirical $\sigma_{\rm core}$
  is large enough that z$<$-2 also collapses to hard-dead --- none
  of the live bins are statistically distinguishable from the bulk.
  \item At preselect and common levels, z$<$-2 still identifies a
  "halo" of bins with R systematically below the bulk, primarily
  concentrated around the hard-dead tower clusters.
\end{itemize}

