\section{Dead- and Excess-Tower Catalogue}

\subsection{Top dead-in-data towers (fiducial, tight level)}

These are the towers driving the 25\% tight-level deficit.

\begin{table}[H]
  \centering
  \caption{Top-5 dead-in-data towers at the tight selection level in
  $|\eta|<0.7$. $\mu$ is the MC-predicted count normalized to the data
  total.}
  \label{tab:dead_tight}
  \begin{tabular}{rrrrrr}
    \toprule
    $i\eta$ & $i\phi$ & $n_{\rm data}$ & $n_{\rm MC}$ & $\mu$ & $z$ \\
    \midrule
    67 & 86  & 33 & $7.00\times 10^6$ & 338.5 & $-19.4$ \\
    56 & 50  & 26 & $6.36\times 10^6$ & 307.6 & $-20.6$ \\
    62 & 63  & 17 & $5.70\times 10^6$ & 275.6 & $-26.6$ \\
    34 & 164 & 34 & $6.00\times 10^6$ & 290.4 & $-13.9$ \\
    35 & 106 & 16 & $5.56\times 10^6$ & 269.0 & $-27.9$ \\
    \bottomrule
  \end{tabular}
\end{table}

Visual inspection of Fig.~\ref{fig:tight_iso} shows clear horizontal
dead stripes at $i\phi\approx 50$, $\approx 150$, $\approx 210$ spanning
$\sim$10-tower $i\eta$ extent, consistent with whole-column dead
readout. Single-tower dead pixels are scattered throughout the
fiducial. These coordinates should map onto the sPHENIX dead/hot-tower
CDB entries used at the Run-24 calibration stage.

\subsection{Top data-excess towers (fiducial, tight+iso level)}

These are towers where the data has significantly more counts than the
inclusive MC predicts, and the MC statistics
($N_{\rm eff}$) are high enough to rule out a fluctuation.

\begin{table}[H]
  \centering
  \caption{Top-5 data-excess towers at tight+iso in $|\eta|<0.7$. High
  $N_{\rm eff}$ rules out statistical noise.}
  \label{tab:hot_tight_iso}
  \begin{tabular}{rrrrrrr}
    \toprule
    $i\eta$ & $i\phi$ & $n_{\rm data}$ & $n_{\rm MC}$ & $\mu$ & $z$ & $N_{\rm eff}$ \\
    \midrule
    40 & 150 & 54 & $4.68\times 10^4$ & 3.5 & $+2.9$ & 11.6 \\
    46 &  40 & 46 & $2.52\times 10^4$ & 1.9 & $+4.3$ & 37.0 \\
    54 &  32 & 46 & $3.54\times 10^4$ & 2.7 & $+3.9$ & 26.4 \\
    38 &   8 & 44 & $1.58\times 10^4$ & 1.2 & $+3.9$ & 25.6 \\
    42 & 168 & 44 & $1.87\times 10^4$ & 1.4 & $+3.8$ & 24.3 \\
    \bottomrule
  \end{tabular}
\end{table}

These 5 towers have $\sim$40 data clusters each passing tight+iso
selection, while MC predicts $\sim$1--4. Two possibilities:
(a) \textbf{hot towers in data} producing spurious high-ET,
narrow-shape clusters that pass BDT + iso; (b) \textbf{MC mis-modeling}
of a specific topology (e.g. a narrow slice of $\phi$ where the
inclusive MC underpredicts background). The isolation + tight BDT
requirement is strong enough that hot towers would need to be
electronic-noise sources with shower-shape similarity to photons —
plausible for certain failure modes. Recommend cross-check against
run-by-run hot-tower QA lists.

\section{Physics Interpretation}

\subsection{Shower-leakage amplification of dead-tower loss}

The $z<-5$ deficit progression
\[
  3.97\% \xrightarrow{\text{common}} 5.19\%
  \xrightarrow{\text{tight}} 25.05\%
  \xrightarrow{\text{tight+iso}} 53.58\%
\]
is not a linear loss per cut; the jump from common to tight is a
factor of 4.8. A plausibility argument: a dead EMCal tower in the
middle of a photon shower footprint suppresses energy in neighboring
towers via lost deposits, which in turn can shift
$w_{\eta,{\rm cog}x}$ and $w_{\phi,{\rm cog}x}$ out of their tight
windows. If the effective "kill radius" of one dead tower on signal
selection is order $\sim$3--4 towers wide rather than 1, a
$\sim$100-tower dead mask would yield an order-of-magnitude
$\sim$25\% tight-selection loss --- consistent with the observed
jump. This argument is heuristic, not quantitative; a full
toy-simulation cross-check is recommended if a precise breakdown is
needed.

\subsection{Why $z>+2$ grows with tightness}

The $z>+2$ fraction rises from 9\% at preselect to 44\% at tight+iso.
This is dominated by two contributions:
(i) \textbf{Statistical fluctuation} from low MC $N_{\rm eff}$
(median 4.3 at tight — per-bin Poisson $\sigma \approx 50\%$ relative),
(ii) \textbf{Real data excess in specific towers} (see
Table~\ref{tab:hot_tight_iso}). The $|z|>5$ tail is almost purely
one-sided ($z<-5$ bins are 100--3000$\times$ more common than $z>+5$),
confirming that the negative tail is dominated by genuine dead-tower
physics while the positive tail is a mix of stat noise and a handful
of hot-tower outliers.

\subsection{Cross-section bias estimate (tower-count proxy)}
\label{sec:bias}

Three bracketing estimates of the acceptance-mismatch systematic,
in order of increasing conservativeness:

\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Hardest-dead lower bound:} $z<-5$ deficit at
  tight+iso = \textbf{53.6\% (fiducial)}. A-region yield that would
  be recovered if every currently-zero data tower got its
  MC-predicted count. Upper bound on what the systematic could be.
  \item \textbf{All significant deficits:} $z<-2$ deficit at
  tight+iso = \textbf{64.0\% (fiducial)}. Adds partially-suppressed
  bins. Still an upper bound since the z$>$+2 excess bins are
  not accounted for.
  \item \textbf{Net (deficit minus excess):} tight+iso net
  $= 64.0\% - 50.1\% = 13.9\%$; tight net
  $= 38.3\% - 19.6\% = +18.7\%$. Balances statistical fluctuations
  and possible hot-tower contributions in both directions; most
  statistics-robust measure of the true physical mismatch.
\end{enumerate}

We take the net at the \textbf{tight} (not tight+iso) level as a
representative central estimate: $+18.7\%$. The tight+iso level is
more iso-amplified but its $z>+2$ excess (dominated by the top-5
candidate hot towers in Table~\ref{tab:hot_tight_iso}) may be a
non-statistical real data feature, so subtracting it would
overcorrect. The cross-section formula
$\sigma = N_{\rm observed}/(\varepsilon_{\rm MC}\cdot\mathcal{L}\cdot
\Delta)$ implies
\[
  \frac{\sigma_{\rm measured}}{\sigma_{\rm true}}
  = \frac{1}{1 + ({\rm def_{net}}/N_{\rm data})}
  = \frac{1}{1 + 0.187}
  \approx 0.84\,,
\]
so the current measurement underestimates the cross-section by
$\sim$16\% as a representative central estimate, with a gross
$\mathcal{O}(25\%)$ upper bound from the z$<$-5-only accounting at
tight and $\mathcal{O}(54\%)$ at tight+iso.

\section{Direct measurement via mask variants}
\label{sec:mask}

Section~\ref{sec:bias} estimated the acceptance systematic from tower
counts and bin densities --- a proxy. The right number is the
observable shift in the unfolded cross-section when the same
dead-tower list is applied symmetrically to both data and MC. Six
cross-check variants implement exactly that.

\subsection{Mechanism}

A new cluster-loop veto was added to
\texttt{RecoEffCalculator\_TTreeReader.C}: at the top of both cluster
loops (leading-finder and main), if the cluster center tower
$(i\eta, i\phi)$ is flagged in a TH2I binary mask loaded from
\texttt{efficiencytool/tower\_masks\_bdt\_nom.root}, the cluster is
skipped. \textbf{The veto is applied identically to data and MC} (no
\texttt{issim} gate), so the efficiency denominators and numerators
remain self-consistent. Three new YAML keys under \texttt{analysis}:
\texttt{tower\_mask\_on}, \texttt{tower\_mask\_file},
\texttt{tower\_mask\_name}.

The mask file contains 9 TH2I histograms (96$\times$256, 1 = veto):

\begin{table}[H]
  \centering
  \begin{tabular}{lrl}
    \toprule
    histogram & \# masked towers & severity \\
    \midrule
    \texttt{mask\_common\_harddead}      & 412  & data=0, MC live (common level) \\
    \texttt{mask\_common\_harddead\_zlt5} & 990  & + z<-5 (common level) \\
    \texttt{mask\_common\_harddead\_zlt2} & 2934 & + -5<z<-2 (common level) \\
    \texttt{mask\_tight\_harddead}       & 1084 & data=0, MC live (tight level) \\
    \texttt{mask\_tight\_harddead\_zlt5}  & 2177 & + z<-5 (tight level) \\
    \texttt{mask\_tight\_harddead\_zlt2}  & 3547 & + -5<z<-2 (tight level) \\
    \texttt{mask\_or\_harddead}          & 1134 & union of common + tight hd \\
    \texttt{mask\_or\_harddead\_zlt5}     & 2541 & union at z<-5 severity \\
    \texttt{mask\_or\_harddead\_zlt2}     & 5084 & union at z<-2 severity \\
    \bottomrule
  \end{tabular}
\end{table}

Generator: \texttt{efficiencytool/make\_tower\_masks.C}. 9 variants
added to \texttt{efficiencytool/make\_bdt\_variations.py}
(auto-expanded to 27 YAMLs, 9 $\times$ 3 periods). Phase 1 (20 condor
jobs, DI TTree pipeline) + Phase 2 (10 condor jobs, all-range merge +
data + \texttt{CalculatePhotonYield}) for the new allz-nominal + 9
variants completed 2026-04-22.

